# 1. Install Nginx

sudo dnf install -y nginx
sudo systemctl enable nginx
sudo systemctl start nginx

# 2. Install Certbot (for Let’s Encrypt SSL)

sudo dnf install -y certbot python3-certbot-nginx

# 3. Point a domain name to your server
#⚠️ Important: Let’s Encrypt certificates require a domain name (not just an IP).

In your DNS, create an A record pointing jenkins.yourdomain.com → 44.217.190.121.

🌐 Using AWS Route 53 (Amazon’s DNS service)
Open Route 53 in the AWS Console

Go to Services → Route 53 → Hosted Zones.

Select the hosted zone for your domain (e.g., jenkinsmanojdevops.com).
(If you don’t have one yet, you’ll need to create a hosted zone for your domain first.)

Create a new record

Click Create record.

Choose Record type: A – IPv4 address.

Record name:

Leave blank or type @ if you want the root domain (jenkinsmanojdevops.com).

Or type jenkins if you want a subdomain (jenkins.jenkinsmanojdevops.com).

Value: Enter your EC2 public IP → 44.217.190.121.

TTL: Leave default (300 seconds is fine).

Save the record

Click Create records.

Route 53 will now resolve your domain to your EC2 instance.

4. Get SSL certificate

sudo certbot --nginx -d jenkins.yourdomain.com

example : sudo certbot --nginx -d jenkinsmanoj.com

This automatically edits your Nginx config to enable HTTPS.

5. Configure Nginx reverse proxy

Create /etc/nginx/conf.d/jenkins.conf:

nginx
server {
    listen 80;
    server_name jenkinsmanoj.com;
    return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
}

server {
    listen 443 ssl;
    server_name jenkinsmanoj.com;

    ssl_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/jenkinsmanoj.com/fullchain.pem;
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/jenkinsmanoj.com/privkey.pem;

    location / {
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:8080;
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;
    }
}

6. Reload Nginx:


sudo systemctl reload nginx

7. Access Jenkins securely
Now Jenkins is available at:

Code
https://jenkinsmanoj.com
✅ Summary: Yes, install Nginx on the same server. Use it as a reverse proxy with SSL certificates (Let’s Encrypt). Browsers will then connect securely via HTTPS, while Jenkins continues to run on port 8080 internally.

